description:
In db.rs init_data_dir(), the schema creation runs as:

  sqlx::raw_sql(SCHEMA).execute(&pool).await?;

SCHEMA contains 7 DDL statements (6 CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS + 1 CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS) executed without a BEGIN/COMMIT transaction. If the process is killed between statements, the database will be partially initialized. The next run succeeds silently due to IF NOT EXISTS, but the missing index (idx_delivery_pending) will not be created because its CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS already ran and... actually the problem is the opposite: statements before the kill succeed, statements after do not. So the database might be missing tables that later code assumes exist, causing runtime errors on first use.

Fix: wrap the SCHEMA execution in an explicit transaction:
  let mut tx = pool.begin().await?;
  sqlx::raw_sql(SCHEMA).execute(&mut *tx).await?;
  tx.commit().await?;

Note: SQLite DDL is transactional, so this is straightforward.
